The **expected return** is computed as follows: 


$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Expected return}&=\sum_{\text{}}{\text{}_{R}} {\text{(Portfolio weight  $\times$ Expected return)}}
\end{aligned}$$

Where: 

R = Return

Then, let us also compute the portfolio weight of Stock B. This is computed using the same formula from step 6. 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Porfolio weight}&=\dfrac{\text{\$7,430.00}}{\text{\$10,910.00}}\\
&={\textbf{ 68.10\%}}
\end{aligned}$$

**The portfolio weight of Stock A is 68.10%.**

Now that we have determined the portfolio weights of the investments, let us compute the expected return using the formula from step 4. The expected return of the portfolio is computed as follows:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Expected return}&={\text{(31.90\%  $\times$ 8.00\%) + (68.10\% $\times$ 11.00\%}}\\
&= {\text{2.55\% + 7.49\%}}\\
&= {\textbf{10.04\%}}
\end{aligned}$$
